Implement RFC 9457 (Problem Details):
In Spring Boot 3, you no longer need custom Error DTOs. You use the built-in ProblemDetail class.
RFC 9457 (which superseded RFC 7807) is a standard for carrying machine-readable error details in HTTP responses to avoid the need to define new error response formats for HTTP APIs.
Instead of a custom JSON structure, your Spring Boot 3+ microservice returns a standardized application/problem+json body:
    {
      "type": "https://api.yourdomain.com/errors/insufficient-funds",
      "title": "You do not have enough credit.",
      "status": 403,
      "detail": "Your current balance is 30, but the item costs 50.",
      "instance": "/account/12345/msgs/abc",
      "balance": 30
    }
Why it matters: 
It allows generic clients (like a mobile app or a monitoring tool) to understand the error without custom parsing logic for every single service in your cluster.
1. Enable Problem Details in application.yml:
        spring:
          mvc:
            problem-details:
              enabled: true
2. Create a Global Exception Handler:
        Use @RestControllerAdvice to catch specific exceptions and map them to the standard format.
        Java
        @RestControllerAdvice
        public class GlobalExceptionHandler {
            @ExceptionHandler(OrderNotFoundException.class)
            public ProblemDetail handleOrderNotFound(OrderNotFoundException ex, WebRequest request) {
                // Standard RFC 9457 fields
                ProblemDetail problem = ProblemDetail.forStatusAndDetail(
                    HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND, ex.getMessage());
                problem.setTitle("Order Resource Not Found");
                problem.setType(URI.create("https://api.yourdomain.com/errors/not-found"));
                // Custom Extensions (The "hidden" trick for observability)
                problem.setProperty("timestamp", Instant.now());
                // Trace ID is automatically added if Micrometer is configured
                return problem;
            }
        }

Error Mapping in Spring Cloud Gateway:
Since the Gateway is the "front door" of your AKS cluster, it must handle downstream failures gracefully.
     It acts as a "Circuit Breaker" and "Translator" between your internal chaos and the external user.
        The Job: If a downstream Java microservice fails with a timeout or a 503,
        the Gateway shouldn't just pass that raw technical error to the user.
    Aggregation: If Service A is down, the Gateway can map that specific failure to a "Graceful Degradation" response (e.g., returning cached data instead of an error).
    Global Exception Handling: You can implement a GlobalErrorWebExceptionHandler in the Gateway to ensure that even if a service is unreachable, the response still follows the RFC 9457 format mentioned above.
    Security: It strips out sensitive internal stack traces before the error leaves the cluster.
1. Define a Fallback Route:
    If a service is down or slow, use the Circuit Breaker filter to redirect to a local error endpoint.
            @Bean
            public RouteLocator customRouteLocator(RouteLocatorBuilder builder) {
                return builder.routes()
                    .route("order_service", r -> r.path("/orders/**")
                        .filters(f -> f.circuitBreaker(c -> c.setName("orderCB")
                                      .setFallbackUri("forward:/fallback/order-error")))
                        .uri("lb://order-service"))
                    .build();
            }
2. Create the Fallback Controller:
        This ensures the user gets a consistent RFC 9457 response even if the microservice is completely unreachable.
        @RestController
        @RequestMapping("/fallback")
        public class FallbackController {
            @GetMapping("/order-error")
            public ProblemDetail handleOrderServiceFailure() {
                ProblemDetail problem = ProblemDetail.forStatus(HttpStatus.SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE);
                problem.setTitle("Order Service is currently unavailable");
                problem.setDetail("The system is under heavy load or maintenance. Please try again later.");
                return problem;
            }
        }

Observability Integration (Micrometer + OTel):
    Observability turns "I think there's an error" into "I know exactly which line of code failed for User X." 
    In 2026, this is done via OpenTelemetry (OTel) and Micrometer.
Correlation IDs (Trace IDs): 
        When an exception is caught in your @ControllerAdvice, 
        you extract the traceId from the current span and inject it into the RFC 9457 instance or a custom traceId field.
Log Exemplars: 
        Modern observability tools (like Azure Monitor/Grafana) use "Exemplars."
        When you see a spike in a "4xx Error" metric graph, you can click a single data point and immediately see the specific logs and traces that caused that specific spike.
Automated Metrics: Instead of manual logging, you use Micrometer to tag exceptions:
    http.server.requests metric gets tagged with exception=UserNotFoundException and status=404. 
    This allows you to set an Alert in Prometheus if the "UserNotFound" rate exceeds 5% (which might indicate a database sync issue).

To make your errors useful, they must be linked to Traces (where it happened) and Metrics (how often it happens).
1. Add Dependencies:
    <dependency>
        <groupId>io.micrometer</groupId>
        <artifactId>micrometer-observation</artifactId>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>io.micrometer</groupId>
        <artifactId>micrometer-tracing-bridge-otel</artifactId>
    </dependency>
2. Use Observations in Service Layer:
    Instead of just logging, "observe" the code block. If an exception occurs inside, Micrometer automatically tags the metric and trace with the error.
        public void processOrder(String orderId) {
            Observation.createNotStarted("order.process", observationRegistry)
                .lowCardinalityKeyValue("order.id", orderId) // For metrics
                .observe(() -> {
                    // Your business logic here
                    // If an exception is thrown, it's automatically recorded
                    repository.save(orderId);
                });
        }

