Spring Retry:
Spring Retry provides a declarative way to handle this using annotations.
1. Enabling Spring Retry
    To use @Retryable, you must first add the spring-retry dependency to your pom.xml and enable it in your configuration.
    @Configuration
    @EnableRetry
    public class RetryConfig {
        // Configuration beans if needed
    }
2. Using @Retryable
    You apply the annotation directly to the method that might fail (e.g., an external API call or a database operation).
    @Service
    public class ExternalApiService {
    
        @Retryable(
            value = { RemoteAccessException.class, MongoTimeoutException.class }, 
            maxAttempts = 3, 
            backoff = @Backoff(delay = 2000, multiplier = 2)
        )
        public void callRemoteService() {
            System.out.println("Attempting to call service...");
            // Logic that might throw an exception
        }
    }
Key Parameters:
    value / include: Specifies which exceptions should trigger a retry.
    maxAttempts: Total number of attempts (including the first one). Default is 3.
    backoff: Controls the wait time between attempts.
    delay: Initial wait time (e.g., 2000ms).
    multiplier: Each subsequent wait is multiplied by this (e.g., 2s, 4s, 8s). This is known as Exponential Backoff.

3. The Recovery Logic (@Recover)
    If all retry attempts fail, you need a "Plan B." The @Recover annotation defines a fallback method that is called after the maxAttempts are exhausted.
    Rules for @Recover:
        The method must be in the same class as the @Retryable method.
        The first argument must be the Exception type being caught.
        The remaining arguments must match the arguments of the @Retryable method.
    
        @Recover
        public void recover(RemoteAccessException e) {
            System.out.println("All retries failed. Transitioning to fallback logic.");
            // Log the error, send to a Dead Letter Queue, or return a cached value
        }
4. How it Works Internally
    Spring Retry uses AOP (Aspect-Oriented Programming). 
    When you call a @Retryable method, Spring creates a proxy that wraps your call in a while loop.
        Proxy Intercepts: The proxy starts the call.
        Catch Exception: If the specified exception occurs, the proxy checks if maxAttempts is reached.
        Backoff: If attempts remain, it sleeps for the backoff duration.
        Final Failure: If no attempts remain, it looks for a @Recover method or re-throws the exception.

5. Important Constraints
    Self-Invocation: Just like @Transactional, calling a @Retryable method from within the same class (e.g., this.myMethod()) 
                    will not work because it bypasses the Spring Proxy.
    Idempotency: Only retry operations that are idempotent (safe to do multiple times).
    Safe: GET requests, checking a status, updating a record with a fixed value.
    Risky: POSTing a payment, incrementing a counter (unless you have deduplication logic).

6. Comparison: Spring Retry vs. Resilience4j
    While @Retryable is great for simple logic, many modern microservices use Resilience4j, 
        which offers more advanced features like Circuit Breakers.

Feature            Spring Retry                    Resilience4j
Best For           Simple method-level retries    Complex distributed systems
Circuit Breaker    No (Limited)                   Yes (Full Support)
External Config    Harder                         Native support via YAML/Properties


@FeignClient:
    It is a declarative REST client used in Spring Boot applications to simplify communication between microservices.
    Instead of writing boilerplate code to handle HTTP requests (like using RestTemplate or WebClient),
        you define an interface, and Feign handles the implementation details.

What is it?
    When you annotate an interface with @FeignClient, Spring creates a proxy implementation at runtime.
    This allows you to call methods on the interface as if they were local methods, while Feign translates them into HTTP calls under the hood.

Why we prefer @FeignClient
In a microservices environment, @FeignClient is often preferred over RestTemplate for several key reasons:
    Declarative Syntax: It uses standard Spring MVC annotations (@GetMapping, @PostMapping).
            This makes the code much cleaner and easier to read compared to manually constructing URLs and headers.
    Automatic Load Balancing: It integrates natively with Spring Cloud LoadBalancer.
            By simply using the service name (e.g., inventory-service) instead of a hardcoded URL, 
                Feign automatically handles routing requests across multiple instances of that service.
    Built-in Resilience: It works seamlessly with Resilience4j. 
            You can define fallback classes or methods directly in the annotation to handle scenarios where the target service is down.
    Seamless Integration: It automatically handles serialization and deserialization (converting JSON to Java Objects) using Jackson,
            and it integrates easily with Micrometer for observability and tracing.
    Reduced Boilerplate: You don't need to manage HTTP connections, catch low-level IO exceptions, or manually build request bodies for every call.

1. Add Dependencies
    First, ensure you have the Spring Cloud OpenFeign dependency in your pom.xml (for Maven):
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-openfeign</artifactId>
    </dependency>
2. Enable Feign Clients
    In your main application class (the one annotated with @SpringBootApplication),
    you must add the @EnableFeignClients annotation to trigger the scanning of Feign interfaces.
        @SpringBootApplication
        @EnableFeignClients
        public class OrderServiceApplication {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
                SpringApplication.run(OrderServiceApplication.class, args);
            }
        }
3. Define the Feign Client Interface
This is where the magic happens. You define an interface that mirrors the API of the service you want to call.
    @FeignClient(name = "product-service", url = "http://localhost:8082/api/products")
    public interface ProductClient {
    
        @GetMapping("/{id}")
        ProductResponse getProductById(@PathVariable("id") Long id);
    
        @PostMapping
        ProductResponse createProduct(@RequestBody ProductRequest request);
    }
    name: A unique identifier for the client.
    url: The base URL of the service you are calling (this can be moved to a properties file for better environment management).

4. Inject and Use the Client
    Now, you can inject this interface into your service layer just like any other Spring bean.
        @Service
        public class OrderService {
        
            private final ProductClient productClient;
        
            public OrderService(ProductClient productClient) {
                this.productClient = productClient;
            }
        
            public void processOrder(Long productId) {
                // Calling the remote service as if it were a local method
                ProductResponse product = productClient.getProductById(productId);
                
                System.out.println("Processing order for: " + product.getName());
            }
        }
Key Configuration Tips
    Logging: Feign has its own logging levels. To see the request/response details, you can define a Logger.
            Level bean and set the package level to DEBUG in your application.properties.
    Error Handling: You can implement a ErrorDecoder to customize how your application handles 4xx or 5xx errors returned by the remote service.
    Timeouts: Configure connection and read timeouts in your properties file to prevent your application from hanging if the external service is slow:
    
    Properties
    feign.client.config.product-service.connectTimeout=5000
    feign.client.config.product-service.readTimeout=5000
